857
01:03:36,933 --> 01:03:42,697
So as you know, No Child Left Behind has been replaced by Every Student Succeeds Act.

858
01:03:45,119 --> 01:03:50,323
And that legislation begins in 2016-2017 as a transition year with full implementation in 2017-2018.

859
01:03:57,294 --> 01:03:59,215
Now there are several key elements of the act.

860
01:03:59,955 --> 01:04:11,259
I want to give you enough of it so you understand it, but not so much that you get overwhelmed by it because there's an awful lot of pieces and we'll have to break it down a piece at a time in order for it to really be understood.

861
01:04:11,279 --> 01:04:18,641
ESSA comprises nine title grants which provide funding to districts and states.

862
01:04:19,381 --> 01:04:20,882
Currently there are about five or six.

863
01:04:21,762 --> 01:04:24,623
I'm not sure how we count them these days because they keep putting them together.

864
01:04:25,327 --> 01:04:35,012
Title IV grant represents a new funding source, which is an allocation grant for districts in the area of student support services, something that would speak to some of the discussion we had a little bit earlier.

865
01:04:36,033 --> 01:04:49,480
Districts and states are required to conform to the requirements of ESSA, so that No Child Left Behind is now giving way to ESSA, and districts and states now must adopt ESSA rules.

866
01:04:50,391 --> 01:04:58,835
ESSA encourages state agencies to think differently about how best to support low-performing schools as the school improvement grants are no longer available.

867
01:04:59,395 --> 01:05:06,919
So they're asking the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education to talk to us about how we could best benefit from their help.

868
01:05:08,280 --> 01:05:12,542
That should be a very robust discussion, especially in our conference and so on and so forth going forward.

869
01:05:14,523 --> 01:05:19,185
ESSA minimizes Title I prescriptive school and district accountability requirements.

870
01:05:19,962 --> 01:05:28,907
No Child Left Behind had very, very specific things under Title I. The SSA wiped some of it away, but it adds some things that are interesting, too.

871
01:05:30,568 --> 01:05:33,009
Equitable access is perhaps one of the biggest areas.

872
01:05:33,129 --> 01:05:34,370
What is equitable access?

873
01:05:34,750 --> 01:05:36,631
Does it mean every school gets the same thing?

874
01:05:37,311 --> 01:05:40,533
Does it mean it's based on proportion of low income?

875
01:05:40,593 --> 01:05:42,374
Is it based on proportion of high needs?

876
01:05:42,854 --> 01:05:43,234
What is it?

877
01:05:44,055 --> 01:05:45,856
Equitable doesn't automatically mean things.

878
01:05:45,896 --> 01:05:47,337
What if you have a teacher in a school who

879
01:05:48,808 --> 01:05:51,270
$80,000 a year and a teacher makes $60,000 a year.

880
01:05:52,090 --> 01:05:56,413
Is it different or is it the same thing as long as there's a teacher there who's experienced and can do the job?

881
01:05:56,973 --> 01:05:58,594
